. Drawing on innovative theories of gender and race, global justice and neocolonialism, and care and masculinity, renowned and emerging scholars examine recent policy developments and debates in Canada, Sweden, Korea, and Japan and their effects on the lives of female care workers. They show that a truly feminist ethics of care must be grounded in the concrete activities of real people working in transnational webs of social relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist ethics. 0aSocial policy -- Moral and ethical aspects. 0aTransnationalism -- Social aspects. 0aWomen caregivers. 0aWomen foreign workers. 0aWomen household employees. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aGabriel, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankivsky, Olena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahon, Rianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahon, Rianne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOnuki, Hironori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeng, Ito, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, Fiona, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTronto, Joan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsuji, Yuki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dD